% v2 draft — additions to §1 introduction. These slot into the
% existing intro after the 2x2-design-space paragraph and before the
% Contributions list. Two paragraphs to add, plus a revised C2.

% --- New paragraph after the 2x2 design-space discussion ---

A second design axis cuts across the push/pull and post-hoc/runtime
cells: who is the \emph{reader} of the coordination data—the agent
or the framework.  Push designs (CA-MCP, LangGraph handoffs) hand
the framework the writer-side decision and the agent the reader-side
decision; pull designs as in v1 of ET-MCP give the agent both sides.
The intercept layer we describe in
\S\ref{sec:arch:pull-vs-intercept} is a fourth combination:
framework on the reader side, MCP-conformant negative-knowledge
events on the wire.  Intercept gives up the agent's ability to ask
custom questions but eliminates the agent-side decision overhead of
``remember to query'' and the round-trip latency of a separate
\texttt{trace.query} call.  Empirically on a public benchmark
(\S\ref{sec:eval:results:retail-intercept}), the intercept layer
outperforms agent-driven pull, and pull does not outperform a
no-coordination baseline at the scale we test.

% --- Revised C2 contribution bullet (replaces v1's C2) ---

\item \textbf{(C2) Architectural pivot: transparent peer-warning
    injection.}  We introduce \emph{intercept}, a framework-side
    coordination layer that prepends \texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} blocks
    to a tool's response when the tool's \texttt{(name, arguments)}
    matches a peer event from a prior failed trial of the same task.
    The agent's tool surface and prompt are unchanged.  On
    $\tau^2$-bench retail at $n{=}30$ tasks (180 trials,
    Haiku~4.5), intercept reaches pass$^2$ of TODO vs.\ TODO for
    no-coordination and TODO for agent-driven pull (paired
    Wilcoxon, Cliff's $\delta = $TODO).  Intercept also uses
    TODO\% fewer input tokens than no-coordination because the
    framework consults the store at zero LLM cost.  This is the
    first head-to-head architectural comparison of pull-vs-intercept
    for multi-agent coordination on a public benchmark.

% --- Additional contribution to add as C5 ---

\item \textbf{(C5) Anthropic-native $\tau^2$-bench harness.}
    Tau2-bench's bundled litellm-based pipeline produces malformed
    Anthropic-API message histories on multi-turn dual-control
    domains, yielding $\geq30\%$ infra-error rates with stock
    \texttt{LLMAgent} on Anthropic models in our measurements.
    We release a $\sim$300-line drop-in replacement that re-uses
    tau2's domain DB, tools, task definitions, and DB-hash reward
    function but constructs its own conversation state directly
    against the Anthropic Messages API.  Zero infra errors at
    180 trials.  We expect this to be useful infrastructure for
    other groups evaluating Anthropic deployments on $\tau$-bench
    family benchmarks.
